Oct 21 2008 	NEVER AGAIN	We are BlueGreen time share owners, and booked this October trip several months in advance. We wanted to be in Vegas for the Barret-Jackson Auto Auction. We booked a 1 bedroom deluxe room for 4 nights. We arrived at the resort earlier than the 4pm check in time, and our room was ready, the one thing we enjoyed about our stay. The first night in our room was a disaster. The room opposite ours was not occupied, and at 4 am the clock radio in that room went off, waking me and my wife. I went to the desk, explained to them the problem. Security went to that room and obviously hit the snooze button. Just as we went back to sleep, the alarm went off again. A little agitated, I returned to the front desk, and complained again. Once again, security went to that room and cut the alarm off. As we fell asleep again, the alarm went off the third time. Now, very agitated, I returned to the front desk, complained, went back to our room, but unable to sleep. Securiy finally decided to unplug the clock. The resort had an upgrade seminar scheduled for us at 11:30 am, so instead of getting out and exploring Vegas, we stayed in the room until our appointment time. After waiting more than a half hour, we were told that all the sales-persons were busy, and we could wait or reschedule. We declined both, went back to our room, once again agitated, since we lost another half day of our vacation. We had a message on our phone stating we were late for our presentation. Now about the resort in general: We were told that there was a convenience store, 5 restaurants, and 2 liquor stores onsite, which wasn't the case. They are still under construction. We were told there was a game room onsite, and we could not find it. Each floor has a trash chute located behind the elevators. Upon opening the door, trash was piled in the room, as the chute door was locked. There were eggshells on the floor, and after our 4 nights there, the smell and the eggshells were still there. One of the elevators was being worked on, and when the mechanic finished, his sheetrock dust and mess was on the floor in the elevator lobby for 2 days. Calling temselves a &quot;high end&quot; resort, I have to wonder what &quot;high end&quot; means to them. The chair rail and base molding in the hallways had gaps where the two pieces were supposed to be joined, poor quality trim work, not condusive to high end. The exit to the presentation room had the door closer covers laying on the floor, along with some trash and a dead frog or toad. I didn't know there were frogs in the desert. Where the maintainence crew cut a hole in the wall, they didn't bother to patch the hole and finish their work. Now, about our room: We found dirty dishes in the cabinets, and dirty eating utensils in the drawer. The dishwasher was installed crooked, not a big deal, but not condusive to high end construction. The shower stall in our room had tile and grout missing, one tile had a sharp edge. Lighting in the living room was inadequate for reading. The ceiling fan/light fixture in the living room would turn the fan on, but not the light. Seems they would have a seperate switch for the light. The laundry room had no light, making it hard to see the controls. The instructions for the appliances were vague, had to go to the front desk to figure out how to work them. The television stations were limited - we wanted to watch some of the Barret-Jackson Auction on the Speed channel, but coud not get it.I have photos of the items above, but am having trouble downloading them. I will be happy to send them to anyone interested.	
Oct 20 2008 	Better places to stay in Vegas	If you are looking for a hotel in Vegas simply to sleep and rest, this is the resort for you. If you are going to Vegas to experience Vegas DON'T stay here. Aesthetically, this is a great resort. It's brand new, with a modern design, the most comfortable beds and the 1 bedroom deluxe has an amazing shower. These are the only good things I can say about the place.There is nothing to do at the hotel. None of the restaurants/bar/casinos are open. They are all still under construction. We didn't arrive until after 11pm and just wanted to grab a drink before bed. Nada. They don't even have a gift shop with snacks or vending machines available. The staff is not very helpful. The concierge had to look through a magazine to help me and my boyfriend find a place to have a romantic dinner. The timeshare presentation was awful. Their 90-minute presentation turn into 2 hours and 45 minutes. We told the salesmen a handful of time we weren't interested and after he insulted my boyfriend and I told him to stop pushing, we finally we able to leave. The worst part about the stay was the 25-minute walk to and from the strip to the hotel. Club 36 clams to be close to the strip but it's at least 1.5 miles away or a $15 cab ride. Be prepared to spend money on cabs if you didn’t drive to Vegas. The walk is a little scary because of the crazy traffic on Tropicana and there is nothing but dirt surrounding the hotel. I wouldn’t walk this alone at night. If you are not a member with this timeshare, I would spend your money at a different hotel.	
