Sep 27 2008 	This is a timeshare. Renters=no use of kitchenette.	Long story short: We got a deal on travelzoo which cut the price of our room in half. We stayed 4 nights. The staff were very nice and our room was very clean and comfortable, complete with sink, stovetop, microwave/convection oven, dishwasher, blender, coffee maker, refrigerator, and washer/dryer.However, when we arrived at our room we found that there were no dishes nor pots or pans to cook with. When we called the front desk, we were told that renters (because this is a timeshare property) were not allowed use of the kitchenette because it was a health code violation. We had already bought groceries to cook with and everything. Nowhere in the advertisements for Club 36 did we see that it was a timeshare property and that renters could not use the kitchenette.When we talked to the front desk, the manager was willing to give us paper plates and cups, but then called back and said they were out of plates and offered a bottle of wine instead. They were very apologetic about the confusion, but still refused to give us any dishes or pots.Luckily, we were on a roadtrip and had a few cooking utensils ourselves, so we brought those up and used them. The hotel did not lock up anything in the kitchenette, so we could still use the appliances. Sort of like, &quot;don't ask, don't tell.&quot;However, it is a brand new facility. The pool is great and so is the semi-rooftop deck. There is no shuttle service to the strip yet but the walk to MGM is minimal and if you have a car I recommend parking in the MGM lot because it is free.I would recommend Club 36 to those renters who have their own cookware, but to those who don't, they should look elsewhere. If you can't get a deal like we did (for $79 a night) it is not worth the money when you can't use the kitchenette. At $149+ a night, it might be more worthwhile to stay at a hotel that's on the strip so you can walk to your favorite restaurants instead of being stranded in a beautiful room with a kitchenette that you can't use.	
Sep 23 2008 	Wonderful Stay at Club 36	Our stay at Bluegreen’s Club 36 was great. Through the Bluegreen Vacation Club, we reserved two units, a 1 bedroom deluxe and a 1 bedroom standard (the units adjoined one another). Each unit was well decorated and comfortable. Both offered king sized beds and pull out sleeper sofas. The bathroom in the deluxe was much larger than the standard, offering a 2 person double headed shower as well as a separate area with a tub. The kitchen had everything needed with the exception of salt and pepper, a dish drying rack, dish soap, and dishwasher soap. We didn’t have the need for these items since we ate out most often.Overall, the resort is nice… nothing too elaborate and showy like some places in Vegas, but very nice. They offer an indoor pool with a whirlpool. There is also a snack bar in the pool area with limited hours. Just outside the pool area is an deck to sunbathe with plenty of lounge chairs and tables. There is also a shower located on the deck for those who need to rinse off. The only drawback to the sunning area is that it is also the area smokers go. If you do not like smoke, be prepared as it is quite busy with smokers throughout the day.There is wireless internet service available in each unit for a daily or weekly charge. Otherwise, there is an area on 2nd floor set up with 3 computers offering internet use (at the time we were there, only 2 of the computers were operating). They need some signage in this area to let patrons know to limit their time at the computer. I was there from 7:45am – 9:30am waiting while two people were using the computers (one was doing “homework” and was going to be a while). While I was waiting, a line formed with 4 people. The exercise facility is very nice with 3 treadmills, 4 eliptical machines and several weight benches. Four LCD TV’s align the walls for easy viewing.The resort is about one block behind the MGM Grand. There is a sidewalk along Tropicana Blvd. that you could walk along if you were interested in walking to the strip. The resort has plans to offer a shuttle to/from the strip, but it was not operational at the time we were there. Having a car was the way to go for us. We spent most of our gambling time at the MGM, we just pulled up to the front door and had our car parked by the valet. They were quick and pleasant when retrieving our car.Overall, the Bluegreen Club 36 Resort is nice and we will definitely return.	
